  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the conventional advice to contribute to open source—finding \"Good First Issue\" labels—is ineffective. Instead, it recommends scanning your own project dependencies for frustrations you’ve already solved, then contributing fixes or documentation improvements to those libraries. The tone is motivational and slightly humorous, using metaphors like “rage” and “dumb dumb brain” to frame struggles as opportunities. The intended audience is developers who want to start contributing but find the process intimidating. A disclaimer notes that success requires years of dedication and luck.",
